1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,050
Now let's briefly go over each of the options to deal with these anions.

2
00:00:04,050 --> 00:00:07,710
You can consider dropping the rows in your data set if there are

3
00:00:07,710 --> 00:00:12,435
only a few rows with missing values and it won't impact your data analysis significantly.

4
00:00:12,435 --> 00:00:17,250
As you made these 96 rows won't have a severe impact on your statistics like

5
00:00:17,250 --> 00:00:19,770
the average and standard deviation and if you see

6
00:00:19,770 --> 00:00:22,575
that they're not absolutely crucial to answer your problem,

7
00:00:22,575 --> 00:00:23,890
you can safely drop them.

8
00:00:23,890 --> 00:00:26,000
In this case, I'd like to drop the rows that have

9
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:28,570
NA values no matter what column they belong to.

10
00:00:28,570 --> 00:00:33,700
We can quickly do this by using the drop NA function on our DataFrame df.

11
00:00:33,700 --> 00:00:36,380
If we check the results using the.describe function,

12
00:00:36,380 --> 00:00:39,065
we can see the number of rows have reduced.

13
00:00:39,065 --> 00:00:41,030
We can also check using

14
00:00:41,030 --> 00:00:45,910
the clean df isna sum function to confirm that there are zero Na cell.

15
00:00:45,910 --> 00:00:50,150
Consider dropping an entire column when almost all of the values,

16
00:00:50,150 --> 00:00:53,675
like 95 to 98% of the values are missing in a column.

17
00:00:53,675 --> 00:00:57,170
At that point, the values that are present in the column are most likely not

18
00:00:57,170 --> 00:01:01,165
significant for any downstream analysis so the column can safely be dropped.

19
00:01:01,165 --> 00:01:03,290
For example, take a look at this new DataFrame,

20
00:01:03,290 --> 00:01:05,840
which is also consisting of 10,000 rows.

21
00:01:05,840 --> 00:01:09,800
The second column consists of almost entirely missing values.

22
00:01:09,800 --> 00:01:12,275
Using the isna.sum method,

23
00:01:12,275 --> 00:01:17,195
we find that almost 9,900 values of our data had NA values.

24
00:01:17,195 --> 00:01:18,890
At this point, we may determine

25
00:01:18,890 --> 00:01:22,520
the little remaining data that's actually there as part of the second column,

26
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:24,330
doesn't even add value to us.

27
00:01:24,330 --> 00:01:27,440
We can use the pandas drop function specifying the name of

28
00:01:27,440 --> 00:01:31,265
the column that we want to drop in setting the axis parameter to one,

29
00:01:31,265 --> 00:01:35,320
where zero typically indicates rows and one indicates columns.

30
00:01:35,320 --> 00:01:40,070
Now, with the second column assessment score to being dropped from the DataFrame,

31
00:01:40,070 --> 00:01:43,280
we can see that there are no more NA values with

32
00:01:43,280 --> 00:01:48,460
our DataFrame that's coming in from the first column for this particular dataset.

33
00:01:48,460 --> 00:01:52,340
What if you don't want to drop the existing data just because there are

34
00:01:52,340 --> 00:01:56,435
some missing values or the values are actually important to your question.

35
00:01:56,435 --> 00:01:59,270
You can fill an empty cell in a column with the mean,

36
00:01:59,270 --> 00:02:01,805
median, or mode of that column as an example.

37
00:02:01,805 --> 00:02:04,115
This is also known as imputing.

38
00:02:04,115 --> 00:02:08,485
We can impute NAN values by using pandas fill Na function.

39
00:02:08,485 --> 00:02:10,790
For example, let's revisit the dataset with

40
00:02:10,790 --> 00:02:14,735
four missing values in column one and 92 missing values in column two.

41
00:02:14,735 --> 00:02:19,145
We can impute all missing values in our DataFrame with the mean of

42
00:02:19,145 --> 00:02:23,855
each column using the df.mean and df.fillna functions.

43
00:02:23,855 --> 00:02:28,355
Here what we're doing is providing df.mean to the filename method as input,

44
00:02:28,355 --> 00:02:30,755
which will calculate the mean of each column.

45
00:02:30,755 --> 00:02:35,165
Now if we run the sum of the NA after applying the fill Na function,

46
00:02:35,165 --> 00:02:36,395
that does the imputing,

47
00:02:36,395 --> 00:02:39,680
we can see that there's no more missing values in our dataset.

48
00:02:39,680 --> 00:02:44,155
It's strongly recommended to only impute NAN values when needed, though.

49
00:02:44,155 --> 00:02:48,170
It makes more sense to targetly impute NANs on columns for

50
00:02:48,170 --> 00:02:49,910
efficiency reasons rather than on

51
00:02:49,910 --> 00:02:52,790
the whole dataframe for columns and may not even need it.

52
00:02:52,790 --> 00:02:54,740
To impute one specific column,

53
00:02:54,740 --> 00:02:56,000
we use the same syntax,

54
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:01,090
but in this case we replace with df indexed on our column for example,

55
00:03:01,090 --> 00:03:03,215
here we're doing it on assessment score too.

56
00:03:03,215 --> 00:03:05,690
Here you can see only the missing values from

57
00:03:05,690 --> 00:03:09,305
the assessment score two column is replaced or filled in with the mean value.

58
00:03:09,305 --> 00:03:13,165
Whereas the missing values for assessment score one is still there.

59
00:03:13,165 --> 00:03:15,770
It's also critical to perform a quick analysis

60
00:03:15,770 --> 00:03:17,990
of your data after imputing missing values,

61
00:03:17,990 --> 00:03:21,185
like get the average of the column for which you impute and then ask,

62
00:03:21,185 --> 00:03:24,140
does the mean change significantly beyond what I'm comfortable with,

63
00:03:24,140 --> 00:03:26,240
due to imputing the data values?

64
00:03:26,240 --> 00:03:30,230
Here's another thing to keep in mind as it can get really confusing.

65
00:03:30,230 --> 00:03:32,510
The only reason that we're able to apply

66
00:03:32,510 --> 00:03:34,970
the describe function on a dataset that still has

67
00:03:34,970 --> 00:03:39,725
NANs and Pandas is because in Pandas describe ignores missing values.

68
00:03:39,725 --> 00:03:42,530
This means if you're trying to compute the mean of

69
00:03:42,530 --> 00:03:46,040
a dataset before and after dropping rows for comparisons,

70
00:03:46,040 --> 00:03:48,410
you're going to get the same result because it describe as

71
00:03:48,410 --> 00:03:50,915
actually doing just that behind the scenes.

72
00:03:50,915 --> 00:03:53,300
We are using describe here when imputing because

73
00:03:53,300 --> 00:03:55,670
we're changing the data samples rather than just

74
00:03:55,670 --> 00:03:58,100
dropping them so we would like to observe

75
00:03:58,100 --> 00:04:00,895
a change in the summary statistics if there is one.

76
00:04:00,895 --> 00:04:05,795
Here because we only have 96 rows with missing values out of 10,000 rows,

77
00:04:05,795 --> 00:04:07,400
the change is not significant in

78
00:04:07,400 --> 00:04:10,280
the statistics between the cleaned and the original DataFrame.

79
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:12,095
But when you have more missing values,

80
00:04:12,095 --> 00:04:15,145
you're more likely to see more significant changes.

81
00:04:15,145 --> 00:04:19,175
Now another option is to actually just convert your data into categories.

82
00:04:19,175 --> 00:04:23,045
You can also bin values in your columns to create fewer categories.

83
00:04:23,045 --> 00:04:27,485
For many cases, this may not lend you specific advantage when dealing with missing data,

84
00:04:27,485 --> 00:04:29,750
but it's just up to the data wrangler judgment

85
00:04:29,750 --> 00:04:32,645
on whether categories are the best option for your data.

86
00:04:32,645 --> 00:04:36,110
For example, here we're using the pd.cut method to bin

87
00:04:36,110 --> 00:04:39,895
variables in both our columns into four bins each.

88
00:04:39,895 --> 00:04:43,565
Let's take a look at the bins for our second column using value counts.

89
00:04:43,565 --> 00:04:46,580
Note that now in this case we now have four bins that were

90
00:04:46,580 --> 00:04:50,750
created in a fifth bin that's actually still reserved for NAN values.

91
00:04:50,750 --> 00:04:54,080
As we can see when we retrieved the rows that have NaN values

92
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:59,070
using DF indexed by df.is null.any on axis equals to one.

93
00:04:59,070 --> 00:05:01,205
Now, in order to deal with this further,

94
00:05:01,205 --> 00:05:03,815
you could then apply one of the earlier techniques we just covered,

95
00:05:03,815 --> 00:05:08,550
such as removing the rows that have the NA values on top of this binned data.

